##### HodlVault2 Project Rules

Every time you choose to apply a rule(s), explicitly state the rule(s) in the output. You can abbreviate the rule description to a single word or phrase [3, 4].

###### Project Context

- **Purpose:** A secure vault application built with the Quasar framework and a Node.js backend, utilizing smart contracts for decentralized asset management [5, 6].
- **High-Level Goal:** To provide a reliable interface and secure signing backend for managing blockchain-based vaults and automated withdrawal services [5, 6].

###### Readable Code Laws (Target State)

- **Law 1: Avoid Deep Nesting.** Use inversion (guard clauses) to collapse nested structures. Return early so the reader can discard previous conditions from their mind [7-9].
- **Law 2: No Code Duplication.** Extract duplicated logic into shared, reusable functions or service modules. Prioritize modularization over copy-pasting [9, 10].
- **Law 3: Meaningful Naming.** Use descriptive names that reveal intent (e.g., use auxiliary verbs like `isLoading`). Avoid shorthand that only the author understands [9, 11, 12].
- **Extraction Rule:** Extract complex logic into its own named function to provide a "summary" of functionality at a glance [9, 13].

###### Codebase Structure

- `src/components/`: PascalCase Vue components [14, 15].
- `src/services/`: kebab-case JavaScript logic for frontend blockchain/oracle operations [14, 15].
- `server/`: Contains the Express.js API logic and signing services [5, 11].
- `server/api-routes/`: Route definitions using lowercase-with-dashes [16].
- `shared/`: Common TypeScript interfaces and validation logic used by both frontend and backend [11, 17].
- `src/contract/`: CashScript smart contracts (.cash) and related JSON metadata [14].
- `docs/` & `plans/`: Project documentation, reports, and implementation plans [18].

###### Tech Stack

- **Frontend:** Quasar.js (Vue 3/Vite) using JavaScript (ES6) [15, 19].
- **Backend Runtime:** Node.js (Version 20+) [19].
- **Backend Language:** TypeScript [11, 16].
- **Backend Framework:** Express.js [11].
- **Smart Contracts:** CashScript [15].
- **Package Manager:** pnpm (version 10+) [15, 19].

###### Coding Patterns & Conventions

- **Vue Style:** Use Vue 3 Composition API with `<script setup>` syntax [20].
- **Naming:**
  - PascalCase for Vue components.
  - kebab-case for all service, utility, and route files [16, 20].
  - camelCase for functions and variables [16, 20].
  - UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants (e.g., `ORACLE_PUBKEY`) [20].
- **Exports:** Named exports for services/utilities; Default exports for Vue components [16, 17, 20].

###### Backend & TypeScript Standards

- **Return Types:** Always use **explicit return types** for all TypeScript functions [16, 17].
- **Strict Typing:** Define strict interfaces for message passing between the frontend and server [16].
- **Pure Functions:** Use the `function` keyword for pure functions to enhance readability [12, 21].
- **Error Handling:** Use guard clauses for validation; avoid large try/catch blocks unless translating errors for the user [7, 16].

###### Workflow & Formatting Standards

- **Prettier Rules:** Single quotes, **no semicolons**, and 100-character print width [6, 22].
- **Documentation:** Use JSDoc for services. Only include comments for complex logic; ignore the obvious [22-24].
- **Linter:** Cascade must automatically fix lint errors it generates using existing ESLint rules [22].

###### Git Usage

Follow these commit message prefixes (lowercase messages) [22, 24]:

- `feat:` New features
- `fix:` Bug fixes
- `refactor:` Code refactoring
- `docs:` Documentation changes
- `chore:` Maintenance or pnpm updates
- `test:` Adding missing tests

###### Maintenance Principles

- **Keep it Concise:** Only add preferences if Cascade consistently gets a pattern wrong. Concise context reduces hallucinations [25-27].
- **Iterative:** Update this file constantly as you discover new problems or refine your tech stack [26-28].
